{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c737e81c-9bda-4324-a431-70d60bc8fde1","content":"Here's the correct skip attribute for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit v2**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n// or for theories:\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit v3** — same syntax as v2.\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\nAll of these will mark the test as \"skipped\" (not failed) in test results, and the reason string appears in the test output/report.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d968898a-b499-4c3b-ab4b-711e5acdda43","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about skip/ignore attributes across MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. This is a straightforward knowledge question about .NET test frameworks. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to invoke any tools or skills.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer with the correct attributes for each framework.","outputTokens":261,"requestId":"0840:38B4C:1E5CDC:24163C:69EAC2A2"},"id":"6d2f05aa-bf8a-4422-922e-435699af065d","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:08:56.789Z","parentId":"2534a3f7-5d3b-4841-bdef-d6f200627157"}
